Anticoagulation peri-PCI

Source

[!INFO] Summary:

  1. The cornerstone of pharmacology for patients undergoing PCI remains oral dual antiplatelet therapy.
  2. There is scant evidence for pretreatment before coronary anatomy is known.
  3. After PCI, advances in stent technology have reduced DAPT duration from 12 to 6 months in stable patients and 1â€‰month in high bleeding risk.
  4. In high ischaemic, low bleeding risk patients, trial evidence has led to recommendations to extend antiplatelet or low dose anticoagulant (rivaroxaban) therapy beyond 12 months. Although randomised trial evidence of optimal dose is lacking, periprocedural use of anticoagulant therapy with UFH has extensive clinical experience and safety profile.

Coronary intervention causes endothelial damage and predisposes to thrombus formation.
The thrombotic risk significantly reduces after endothelialization of the stent (Several weeks) but does not completely disappear.

  • Before
    • Stable angina
      • All patients should be pre-treated with aspirin.
      • If PCI is very likely, pre treatment with clopidogrel 600mg at least 2 hours before the procedure is recommended.
    • NSTE-ACS
      • Aspirin (loading and maintenance)
      • Ticagrelor 180 or Clopidogrel 600 as soon as coronary anatomy is established.
      • Anticoagulation: Fondaparinux (enoxaparin if fondaparinux isn't available) is best for pre treatment. During treatment, UFH is best.
    • STEMI
      • Ticagrelor or prasugrel before STEMI.
  • During PCI
    • Stable Angina
      • intra-procedure -> Anticoagulate with UFG or bivalirudin.
      • Anticoagulation is stopped after the procedure.
    • NSTE-ACS and STEMI
      • UFH is used.
  • After

Cocaine

Even casual use of cocaine may be associated with acute or chronic cardiovascular toxicity

  • Arrhythmias
  • Acute MI
  • Chronic cardiomyopathy
  • Coronary artery disease
  • Acute hypertension

Cocaine inhibits norepinephrine reuptake. Therefore, it potentiates sympathetic stimulation.
